{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CrRvYY2xJz1A2Z9b1TzEom","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]\n3\tlastStep: 8\n4\tstatus: 'complete'\n5\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-02'\n6\tinputDocuments:\n7\t  - prd-evaluator-redesign.md\n8\t  - research/domain-harness-design-long-running-agents-research-2026-04-01.md\n9\t  - research/technical-ai-agent-verification-testing-research-2026-03-16.md\n10\t  - research/technical-workflow-engine-implementation-research-2026-04-02.md\n11\t  - architecture.md (v1 architecture, brownfield context)\n12\tworkflowType: 'architecture'\n13\tproject_name: 'codeharness'\n14\tuser_name: 'BMad'\n15\tdate: '2026-04-02'\n16\t---\n17\t\n18\t# Architecture Decision Document\n19\t\n20\t_This document builds collaboratively through step-by-step discovery. Sections are appended as we work through each architectural decision together._\n21\t\n22\t## Project Context Analysis\n23\t\n24\t### Requirements Overview\n25\t\n26\t**Functional Requirements:** 43 FRs across 10 capability areas — Workflow Definition (6), Agent Configuration (6), Workflow Configuration (3), Workflow Execution (8), Adversarial Verification (5), Feedback Loop (3), Circuit Breaker (4), Observability (2), CLI Commands (4), Legacy Removal (2).\n27\t\n28\t**Non-Functional Requirements:** 18 NFRs across Performance (5), Reliability (5), Integration (4), Code Quality (4). Architecture-critical NFRs: crash recovery via state persistence (NFR6-8), programmatic agent dispatch only (NFR11), optional observability (NFR14).\n29\t\n30\t**Scale & Complexity:**\n31\t- Primary domain: Developer tooling (CLI + plugin)\n32\t- Complexity level: High\n33\t- Estimated architectural components: ~10\n34\t- Cross-cutting concerns: config resolution chain, trace ID propagation, crash recovery, evaluator isolation\n35\t\n36\t### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n37\t\n38\t- Runtime: Node.js (TypeScript)\n39\t- Dependencies: `commander`, `yaml`, `@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`\n40\t- Execution substrate: Agent SDK `query()` — async generator, session management, JSON schema output\n41\t- State: Single `workflow-state.yaml` in repo (beads-level simplicity)\n42\t- Evaluator isolation: Separate workspace, no source code, Docker container for artifact\n43\t- Docker: Required for evaluator but graceful degradation if missing (Journey 5)\n44\t\n45\t### Cross-Cutting Concerns\n46\t\n47\t1. **Config resolution** — every agent/workflow dispatch resolves embedded → user → project patches\n48\t2. **Trace ID propagation** — generated per iteration, injected into agent prompts, correlates to observability\n49\t3. **Crash recovery** — state persisted after each task, engine resumes from last checkpoint\n50\t4. **Evaluator isolation** — separate workspace, `disallowedTools` enforcement, `source_access: false`\n51\t\n52\t## Starter Template Evaluation\n53\t\n54\t### Primary Technology Domain\n55\t\n56\tCLI developer tool — Node.js/TypeScript. Brownfield project with established toolchain.\n57\t\n58\t### Starter Options: Not Applicable (Brownfield)\n59\t\n60\tExisting project toolchain is retained:\n61\t\n62\t| Decision | Current (Keep) | Source |\n63\t|----------|---------------|--------|\n64\t| Language | TypeScript (strict) | Existing project |\n65\t| Build | tsup | Existing project |\n66\t| Test | vitest (unit) + BATS (integration) | Existing project |\n67\t| CLI | commander | Existing project |\n68\t| YAML | yaml package | Existing project |\n69\t| **New** | @anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk | Research — replaces bash spawn |\n70\t\n71\t**No starter template needed.** One new dependency added. Internals reworked.\n72\t\n73\t## Core Architectural Decisions\n74\t\n75\t### Decision Priority Analysis\n76\t\n77\t**Critical Decisions (Block Implementation):**\n78\t1. Module boundaries — what code goes where\n79\t2. Evaluator workspace isolation — how to enforce source-free verification\n80\t3. Evaluator verdict schema — the contract between evaluator and engine\n81\t\n82\t**Important Decisions (Shape Architecture):**\n83\t4. Embedded template storage — where agent/workflow YAML files live in the package\n84\t5. Config resolution caching — resolve once or every dispatch\n85\t\n86\t**Deferred Decisions (Post-MVP):**\n87\t- PersonaNexus trait compilation algorithm (Growth phase)\n88\t- Pluggable evaluator strategies interface (Growth phase)\n89\t- Workflow marketplace format/registry (Vision phase)\n90\t\n91\t### AD1: Module Boundaries\n92\t\n93\t| Module | Responsibility | Key FRs |\n94\t|--------|---------------|---------|\n95\t| `workflow-parser` | Parse YAML, validate against JSON schema, resolve patches (embedded→user→project) | FR1-6, FR13-15 |\n96\t| `agent-resolver` | Resolve agent config through patch chain, compile to SDK inline subagent definition | FR7-12 |\n97\t| `workflow-engine` | Execute flow steps, manage iterations, handle `loop:` blocks, inject evaluator findings into retries | FR16-18, FR29-31 |\n98\t| `agent-dispatch` | Call Agent SDK `query()`, manage sessions (fresh/continue), inject trace IDs | FR19-23 |\n99\t| `evaluator` | Blind evaluator workspace setup, spawn, JSON verdict parsing | FR24-28 |\n100\t| `circuit-breaker` | Score-based stagnation detection, score history tracking | FR32-35 |\n101\t| `workflow-state` | Read/write workflow-state.yaml, crash recovery (resume from last completed task) | NFR6-8 |\n102\t\n103\t**Rationale:** 7 modules, each 100-200 LOC. Feedback loop (FR29-30) is part of `workflow-engine` — it's loop logic, not a separate concern. CLI commands (`init`, `run`, `validate`, `status`) are thin wrappers calling these modules. Observability (FR36-37) is a cross-cutting concern handled by trace ID injection in `agent-dispatch`, not a separate module.\n104\t\n105\t### AD2: Evaluator Workspace Isolation\n106\t\n107\t**Decision:** Temp directory with only story files + Docker access.\n108\t\n109\t```\n110\t/tmp/codeharness-verify-{runId}/\n111\t  story-files/     # copied ACs from sprint\n112\t  verdict/         # evaluator writes JSON verdict here\n113\t```\n114\t\n115\tEngine copies story files to temp dir, spawns evaluator with `cwd` set to this directory. Agent SDK options enforce isolation:\n116\t- `bare: true` — no plugins, hooks, MCP, memory\n117\t- `disallowedTools: [\"Edit\", \"Write\"]` — read-only + execute only\n118\t- `cwd: /tmp/codeharness-verify-{runId}` — no source code present\n119\t\n120\t**Rationale:** Simplest approach. Source isn't there because we never put it there. No git worktree complexity, no Docker-in-Docker. The Agent SDK's `cwd` + `disallowedTools` provide sufficient isolation.\n121\t\n122\t### AD3: Embedded Template Storage\n123\t\n124\t**Decision:** `templates/` directory in the npm package.\n125\t\n126\t```\n127\ttemplates/\n128\t  agents/\n129\t    dev.yaml\n130\t    qa.yaml\n131\t    architect.yaml\n132\t    pm.yaml\n133\t    sm.yaml\n134\t    analyst.yaml\n135\t    ux-designer.yaml\n136\t    tech-writer.yaml\n137\t    evaluator.yaml\n138\t  workflows/\n139\t    default.yaml\n140\t```\n141\t\n142\tIncluded via `package.json` `files` array. Readable, editable for debugging, consistent with existing pattern (`templates/Dockerfile.verify`).\n143\t\n144\t**Rationale:** Files over compiled strings. Easier to inspect, diff, and debug. The `codeharness init` command copies the default workflow to the project; embedded agents are resolved at runtime from the package location.\n145\t\n146\t### AD4: Config Resolution Caching\n147\t\n148\t**Decision:** Resolve all configs once at engine startup, cache in memory.\n149\t\n150\tOn `codeharness run`:\n151\t1. Resolve workflow: load embedded → apply user patch → apply project patch → cache\n152\t2. Resolve all referenced agents: same resolution chain → cache\n153\t3. Run engine with cached configs — no file I/O during execution\n154\t\n155\t**Rationale:** Config files don't change during a run. Caching guarantees NFR2 (<200ms resolution) and eliminates repeated file system reads during long-running execution.\n156\t\n157\t### AD5: Evaluator Verdict Schema\n158\t\n159\t**Decision:** Structured JSON enforced by Agent SDK `jsonSchema` option.\n160\t\n161\t```typescript\n162\tinterface EvaluatorVerdict {\n163\t  verdict: 'pass' | 'fail';\n164\t  score: {\n165\t    passed: number;\n166\t    failed: number;\n167\t    unknown: number;\n168\t    total: number;\n169\t  };\n170\t  findings: Array<{\n171\t    ac: number;\n172\t    description: string;\n173\t    status: 'pass' | 'fail' | 'unknown';\n174\t    evidence: {\n175\t      commands_run: string[];\n176\t      output_observed: string;\n177\t      reasoning: string;\n178\t    };\n179\t  }>;\n180\t  evaluator_trace_id: string;\n181\t  duration_seconds: number;\n182\t}\n183\t```\n184\t\n185\t**Rationale:** Replaces the 175-line proof document regex parser entirely. The Agent SDK validates the output against this schema — if the evaluator doesn't produce valid JSON, the SDK rejects it. Every AC verdict requires evidence (commands + output), enforcing the anti-leniency principle structurally.\n186\t\n187\t### Decision Impact Analysis\n188\t\n189\t**Implementation Sequence:**\n190\t1. `workflow-state` — foundation for crash recovery, needed by everything\n191\t2. `workflow-parser` — parse YAML + resolve patches, needed before execution\n192\t3. `agent-resolver` — resolve agent configs, needed before dispatch\n193\t4. `agent-dispatch` — SDK integration, needed before engine can run\n194\t5. `workflow-engine` — orchestrates everything above\n195\t6. `evaluator` — depends on dispatch + state\n196\t7. `circuit-breaker` — depends on evaluator verdicts\n197\t\n198\t**Cross-Component Dependencies:**\n199\t- `workflow-engine` depends on all other modules\n200\t- `evaluator` depends on `agent-dispatch` (for SDK spawn) and `workflow-state` (for verdict recording)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017HxP1cbYsBpSzeobjawugj","session_id":"655665ef-6468-4ba6-a46a-b395b1530cdd","uuid":"6570c00b-f1ed-4cb6-b04a-bf0475b87f9a","timestamp":"2026-04-02T11:46:12.328Z"}
